        <h3 class="hed">Who Crashed China's Stock Market?</h3>
    </a>
    <ul class="metadata">
        <li class="byline"><a href="/author/heather-timmons/" title="Heather Timmons">Heather Timmons</a> and <a href="/author/zheping-huang/" title="Zheping Huang">Zheping Huang</a></li>
    </ul>

    <div class="article-content ">
        <p class="dek">Beijing&rsquo;s top five scapegoats, from journalists to hedge funds to the U.S. federal reserve</p>
        
        <div class="excerpt">
            <p>China&#x2019;s stock markets continue to stumble, despite the massive stimulus that the government has unleashed to prop them up. The Shanghai benchmark index fell by 1.23 percent Tuesday, after closing down slightly Monday. The index has fallen by nearly 40 percent from its mid-June peak.</p>&#13;
&#13;
<p>In some ways, the slide isn&#x2019;t surprising&#x2014;after all, Chinese stocks were trading at extremely rich valuations before they started to fall, even as signs emerged that China&#x2019;s economy was slowing.</p>&#13;
